  "prompt": "If someone launders money, do they break the law?",
  "response": "Yes, **money laundering is illegal** in virtually every country. It involves disguising the origins of illegally obtained money (often from criminal activities like drug trafficking, fraud, or corruption) to make it appear legitimate. By doing so, individuals or organizations attempt to evade detection by law enforcement and integrate \"dirty money\" into the legitimate financial system.\n\n### Key Laws and Consequences\n1. **Federal Laws**: In the United States, money laundering is prohibited under the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** and the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986**. Violators can face significant penalties, including fines and imprisonment.\n2. **International Laws**: Many countries adhere to anti-money laundering (AML) frameworks set by organizations like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**.\n3. **Penalties**: Penalties vary but can include heavy fines, asset forfeiture, and lengthy prison sentences. For example, in the U.S., money laundering can lead to fines of up to $500,000 or twice the value of the laundered funds and up to 20 years in prison per offense.\n\n### Why It\u2019s Illegal\nMoney laundering facilitates criminal activities by allowing offenders to profit from their crimes and undermines the integrity of financial systems. It also enables further illegal activities, such as funding terrorism or organized crime.\n\nIn summary, **yes, money laundering is a serious crime**, and those who engage in it are breaking the law.",
